% ============================================================
\begin{abstract}
Recent work has established that Big Five personality traits can be linearly extracted and steered in LLMs. We build on this foundation by asking \emph{where}, \emph{why}, and \emph{how far}: where in the network does personality causally matter (not just exist), why does trait independence vary across architectures, and how do psychological constructs beyond the Big Five---specifically defense mechanisms---manifest geometrically? Using contrastive activation analysis and causal intervention across five models---Qwen3-0.6B, Qwen2.5-0.5B, TinyLlama-1.1B, Llama-3.2-1B, and Gemma-2-2B---we report five findings: \textbf{(1)~Existence--Causation Dissociation:} Personality information grows stronger through deeper layers (probe accuracy $\ge0.91$, consistent with recent probing studies), yet activation patching reveals that \emph{causal influence} is concentrated in the earliest attention layers---a gap between where information \emph{exists} versus where it \emph{causally matters}. \textbf{(2)~Architecture-Dependent Factor Independence:} Big Five trait independence varies substantially across architectures (mean off-diagonal $|\cos|$ from 0.05 to 0.42), indicating that model capacity and training recipe jointly shape trait factorization. \textbf{(3)~Hierarchical Defense Mechanism Geometry:} All nine defense mechanisms from Vaillant's hierarchy show activation-space clustering that mirrors psychological maturity levels: immature defenses form correlated subspaces ($|\cos|=0.511$) while mature defenses are near-orthogonal ($0.030$)---a 17-fold difference preserved across all five architectures. \textbf{(4)~Architecture-Specific Steering Bounds:} Maximum tolerable intervention strength varies from $|\alpha|=1.0$ to $10.0$, but our Relative Injection Strength (RIS) metric reveals that this largely reflects residual stream scale differences. \textbf{(5)~RLHF Alignment Tax on Steerability:} BFI-44 dose-response analysis reveals that RLHF-reinforced traits (Agreeableness, Conscientiousness) resist activation steering while value-neutral traits (Extraversion, Neuroticism) are highly controllable---a pattern consistent across architectures. We introduce \textbf{PersonaLens}, a standardized framework for mechanistic personality analysis integrating contrastive extraction, causal localization, and psychometric validation.
\end{abstract}

\keywords{Mechanistic Interpretability \and Personality \and Representation Engineering \and Activation Steering \and Large Language Models}

% ============================================================
\section{Introduction}\label{sec:intro}

Large Language Models (LLMs) readily adopt distinct \emph{personas} when instructed through system prompts, producing text that reflects specific personality traits \citep{shanahan2023role}. This ability has enabled applications ranging from immersive role-playing \citep{chen2024rolesurvey} to personality-consistent dialogue agents \citep{shao2023character}. However, a fundamental question remains: \textbf{do these personality behaviors correspond to structured internal representations, and can we identify and control them mechanistically?}

Prior work on LLM personality has largely taken a \emph{behavioral} perspective: evaluating model outputs against psychometric instruments such as the Big Five \citep{jiang2024evaluating}, or engineering prompts to elicit desired traits \citep{serapiogarcía2023personality}. While valuable, this approach treats the model as a black box and cannot answer whether personality traits correspond to identifiable neural structures.

Meanwhile, the field of \emph{representation engineering} \citep{zou2023representation} has demonstrated that semantic concepts---truthfulness \citep{li2024iti}, harmlessness \citep{rimsky2024steering}, and emotional states \citep{bao2024emotion}---correspond to linear directions in activation space that can be both probed and manipulated. Recent work has begun extending this paradigm to personality: persona vectors \citep{chen2025persona}, activation-space personality steering \citep{sun2025activation}, and persona blending \citep{billy2025blending} all suggest that personality traits may occupy distinct linear subspaces within transformer representations.

However, the field currently lacks a \textbf{standardized, model-agnostic methodology} for systematically analyzing personality representations across different models. Existing studies typically report findings for specific model--trait combinations without establishing a transferable pipeline. Furthermore, no prior work jointly analyzes Big Five traits and psychological defense mechanisms within a unified framework, despite defense mechanisms being critical to authentic personality expression \citep{personaforge2025}.

\paragraph{Research Questions.} This work addresses four fundamental questions about personality representation in LLMs:
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*,topsep=2pt,itemsep=1pt]
    \item \textbf{Q1 (Representation Existence):} Do personality traits correspond to linearly separable directions in LLM activation space, and how does this separability vary across architectures and depth?
    \item \textbf{Q2 (Geometric Structure):} Are different personality dimensions encoded independently---as predicted by the Big Five's orthogonal factor structure---and does defense mechanism geometry mirror psychological maturity hierarchies?
    \item \textbf{Q3 (Causal Relevance):} Where in the network do personality representations \emph{causally influence} output, and does this coincide with where they are most \emph{detectable}?
    \item \textbf{Q4 (Controllability):} Can extracted personality directions enable reliable inference-time behavioral control, what are the architectural limits of such control, and can it penetrate safety guardrails that prompt-based methods cannot?
\end{enumerate}

\paragraph{Contributions.} Building on recent advances in personality probing and steering \citep{frising2025linear, feng2026persona, chen2025persona, ju2025probing}, this work investigates the \emph{structure}, \emph{causality}, and \emph{limits} of personality representations. We make five contributions:
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*,topsep=2pt,itemsep=1pt]
\item \textbf{Existence--Causation Dissociation:} Through activation patching across five architectures, we show that personality information \emph{exists} most strongly in middle-to-upper layers (probe accuracy $\ge$0.91, consistent with \citet{ju2025probing}), yet \emph{causally influences} output primarily through the earliest attention layers. This dissociation---between detectability and causal relevance---has direct implications for where steering interventions should be applied (Sec.~\ref{sec:localization}).
\item \textbf{Architecture-Dependent Personality Geometry:} We find that Big Five trait independence varies across architectures (mean off-diagonal $|\cos|$ from 0.05 to 0.42 across five models), with same-layer comparison, null baselines, and shuffle-label controls. This complements single-model orthogonality findings \citep{feng2026persona} by revealing that model capacity and training recipe jointly shape the degree of trait factorization (Sec.~\ref{sec:orthogonality}).
\item \textbf{Defense Mechanism Hierarchy in Activation Space:} We extend the analysis beyond the Big Five to all nine defense mechanisms from Vaillant's hierarchy \citep{vaillant1986empirical}. Activation-space clustering mirrors psychological maturity levels: immature defenses form correlated subspaces ($|\cos|=0.511$) while mature defenses are near-orthogonal ($0.030$)---a 17-fold difference preserved across all five architectures ($p < 0.00013$ by combinatorial ordering test), providing neural evidence for hierarchical psychological organization (Sec.~\ref{sec:results_ortho}).
\item \textbf{Architecture-Specific Steering Bounds and RIS Normalization:} Maximum tolerable intervention strength varies from $|\alpha|=1.0$ to $10.0$ across architectures. We introduce the Relative Injection Strength (RIS) metric that normalizes for residual stream scale, revealing that apparent cross-model variability largely reflects scale differences rather than qualitative fragility (Sec.~\ref{sec:steering}).
\item \textbf{RLHF Alignment Tax on Steerability:} BFI-44 dose-response analysis across all five Big Five traits reveals that RLHF-reinforced traits (Agreeableness, Conscientiousness) resist activation steering while value-neutral traits (Extraversion, Neuroticism) are highly controllable. Activation steering also penetrates AI identity guardrails that prompt-based methods cannot bypass (4.6/5.0 vs 3.6/5.0 human evaluation). Both patterns replicate across architectures (Sec.~\ref{sec:baselines}, \ref{sec:bfi44}).
\end{enumerate}
\paragraph{Methodological Contribution.} To enable these discoveries, we introduce \textbf{PersonaLens}, a standardized pipeline that:
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*,topsep=2pt,itemsep=1pt]
\item \textbf{Defines a contrastive dataset} covering all five Big Five dimensions and three representative defense mechanisms, with carefully designed prompt pairs that isolate individual trait dimensions (Sec.~\ref{sec:data}).
\item \textbf{Extracts multi-method personality directions}---RMS-normalized difference vectors, PCA-based directions, and Leave-One-Scenario-Out (LOSO) cross-validated linear probes---producing converging evidence robust to extraction method choice (Sec.~\ref{sec:extraction}).
\item \textbf{Establishes causal importance} through token-localized and component-level activation patching, distinguishing information existence from causal influence (Sec.~\ref{sec:localization}).
\item \textbf{Validates across five architecturally diverse models} (Qwen, LLaMA, Gemma), revealing remarkable structural consistency alongside architecture-specific differences (Sec.~\ref{sec:results}).
\end{enumerate}

% ============================================================
\section{Related Work}\label{sec:related}

\paragraph{Personality in LLMs.}
The study of personality expression in LLMs has expanded rapidly. Foundational surveys \citep{serapiogarcía2023personality} establish that LLMs can simulate Big Five personality traits via prompting. Personality Alignment \citep{mao2024personality} introduces training-free alignment via Personality Activation Search (PAS). PersonaForge \citep{personaforge2025} proposes psychology-grounded architecture with dual-process generation but operates entirely at the prompt level. Our work extends PersonaForge by grounding its psychological constructs in neural representations.

\paragraph{Representation Engineering and Activation Steering.}
Representation Engineering (RepE) \citep{zou2023representation} establishes that high-level concepts correspond to linear directions in activation space. Inference-Time Intervention (ITI) \citep{li2024iti} demonstrates that shifting activations along truthful directions improves model truthfulness. Contrastive Activation Addition \citep{rimsky2024steering, turner2023activation} generalizes this to behavioral attributes. More recent advances investigate context-dependent control via Steering Vector Fields (SVF) \citep{svf2026} and formalize the algebraic structure of these directions through factored subspaces \citep{factored2026}.

\paragraph{Personality-Specific Representation Engineering.}
A rapidly growing body of work applies RepE specifically to personality traits. Frising and Balcells~\citep{frising2025linear} ground linear probing and steering in Big Five psychometric scales using Llama~3.3~70B, finding that linear directions are effective probes but that steering capabilities are \emph{context-dependent}---reliable in forced-choice tasks but limited in open-ended generation. PERSONA~\citep{feng2026persona} introduces activation vector algebra (scalar multiplication, addition, subtraction) for compositional personality control, claiming approximately orthogonal trait directions and achieving near-SFT performance on PersonalityBench. Bhandari et al.~\citep{bhandari2026activation} propose hybrid layer selection for stable trait control, discovering that personality traits occupy a low-rank shared subspace. Chen et al.~\citep{chen2025persona} extract persona vectors for personality steering, and BILLY~\citep{billy2025blending} blends multiple persona vectors for creative generation. Recent works have also developed the PERSONA frameworks~\citep{persona2026, persona2025} for mapping personality representations using trait vectors and hybrid layer subspaces. On the application side, Ong et al.~\citep{ong2025identifying} apply Big Five steering vectors to study cooperative behavior in multi-agent Prisoner's Dilemma settings, demonstrating that personality steering has downstream behavioral consequences.

These works collectively establish that personality traits can be linearly extracted and steered. Our work builds on this foundation in three directions: (1)~we add \emph{causal localization} via activation patching, distinguishing where personality information exists from where it causally matters; (2)~we extend the analysis to psychological defense mechanisms, validating geometric structure against Vaillant's maturity hierarchy; and (3)~we test trait independence across five diverse architectures, revealing architecture-dependent variation in orthogonality.

\paragraph{Layer-wise Personality Encoding.}
Ju et al.~\citep{ju2025probing} conduct the most comprehensive layer-wise probing study to date, testing 11 open-source LLMs and finding that personality is predominantly encoded in middle and upper layers, with instruction-tuned models showing clearer trait separation. Their layer-wise perturbation method successfully edits personality during inference with minimal capability degradation. Our probing results are consistent with theirs (probe accuracy $\ge 0.91$ in middle-to-late layers across all five tested models). We complement their probing analysis with activation patching, which reveals an additional dimension: while personality information \emph{grows stronger} through depth, \emph{causal influence} on output is concentrated in the earliest attention layers. This existence--causation dissociation suggests that optimal steering strategy depends on whether the goal is to maximize representational signal (middle layers) or causal leverage (early layers).

\paragraph{Steering Frameworks.}
On the engineering side, EasySteer \citep{xu2025easysteer} provides a unified, high-performance framework for LLM steering built on vLLM, supporting multiple vector extraction methods (DiffMean, PCA, SAE) and learning-based approaches (LoReFT) across eight application domains including personality. While EasySteer demonstrates the practical viability of activation steering at production scale, it focuses on \emph{engineering infrastructure} rather than scientific analysis of how personality is represented. Our work is complementary: PersonaLens provides the \emph{scientific foundation}---psychometrically grounded methodology, geometric structure analysis, causal localization, and cross-model validation---that informs and validates the engineering practice enabled by frameworks like EasySteer.

\paragraph{Mechanistic Interpretability and Reliability Constraints.}
From Traits to Circuits \citep{bao2025traits2circuits} proposes identifying ``personality circuits'' as minimal subgraphs responsible for trait expression. While linear probing finds personality directions effective \citep{konen2025probing}, broad empirical evaluations highlight fragility in Out-of-Distribution (OOD) transfer and collateral capability degradation during concept activation steering \citep{cae2025, cae2025b}. To improve reliability, recent techniques denoise concept vectors using Sparse Autoencoders (SAEs) \citep{sae2025denoising}. Furthermore, dissociations between magnitude and directional steering \citep{direction2026} provide crucial insights for continuous behavioral modulation.

\paragraph{Non-Identifiability Concerns.}
Venkatesh and Kurapath~\citep{venkatesh2026nonidentifiability} raise important theoretical concerns: persona vectors are fundamentally non-identifiable under single-layer white-box access due to null-space ambiguity. While we acknowledge this limitation, we argue that our multi-method approach provides converging evidence that is robust to the specific choice of extraction method.

% ============================================================
\section{PersonaLens Framework}\label{sec:method}

PersonaLens consists of five modular phases (Fig.~\ref{fig:pipeline}), each designed to be model-agnostic and applicable to any transformer architecture.

\begin{figure}[t]
\centering
\fbox{\parbox{0.95\textwidth}{\small
\textbf{Phase 1: Contrastive Data Construction} (Sec.~\ref{sec:data})\\
$\rightarrow$ Paired prompts $(x^+_i, x^-_i)$ for each trait \\[4pt]
\textbf{Phase 2: Activation Collection} (Sec.~\ref{sec:collection})\\
$\rightarrow$ Hidden states $h_\ell(x^+_i), h_\ell(x^-_i)$ at all layers $\ell$ \\[4pt]
\textbf{Phase 3: Persona Vector Extraction} (Sec.~\ref{sec:extraction})\\
$\rightarrow$ Personality directions $v_\ell$ per layer via mean-diff / PCA / probe \\[4pt]
\textbf{Phase 4: Causal Localization} (Sec.~\ref{sec:localization})\\
$\rightarrow$ Causal importance $\mathcal{I}(\ell)$ via activation patching \\[4pt]
\textbf{Phase 5: Personality Steering} (Sec.~\ref{sec:steering})\\
$\rightarrow$ Inject $v_\ell$ during inference: $\tilde{h}_\ell = h_\ell + \alpha \cdot v_\ell$
}}
\caption{The PersonaLens pipeline. Each phase is independently executable and produces standardized outputs that enable cross-model comparison.}
\label{fig:pipeline}
\end{figure}

% ============================================================
\subsection{Phase 1: Contrastive Data Construction}\label{sec:data}

Following the contrastive activation paradigm \citep{zou2023representation, rimsky2024steering}, we construct paired prompts designed to elicit contrasting personality states while keeping the conversational scenario identical.

\paragraph{Big Five Traits.}
For each of the five personality dimensions---Openness (O), Conscientiousness (C), Extraversion (E), Agreeableness (A), and Neuroticism (N)---we define:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*,topsep=2pt,itemsep=1pt]
\item A \textbf{high-trait system prompt} instructing the model to behave as a person with an extreme level of the trait;
\item A \textbf{low-trait system prompt} instructing the opposite extreme;
\item $K=20$ \textbf{neutral scenario prompts} (user messages) spanning diverse social, emotional, and decision-making contexts.
\end{itemize}

For example, an Openness pair uses the system prompts ``\textit{You are extremely open to new experiences, intellectually curious, imaginative\ldots}'' vs.\ ``\textit{You are very practical, conventional, and prefer routine\ldots}'', with shared scenarios like ``\textit{What do you think about modern abstract art?}''

\paragraph{Defense Mechanisms.}
Following Vaillant's hierarchy \citep{vaillant1994ego} and PersonaForge's operationalization \citep{personaforge2025}, we construct contrastive pairs for three representative defense mechanisms: Humor, Rationalization, and Projection. These three mechanisms were selected as they represent distinct categories in Vaillant's hierarchy (mature, neurotic, and immature defenses respectively), providing coverage of the defense mechanism construct space. Each mechanism contrasts an \emph{active} condition (the mechanism is deployed in response to a stressor) against a \emph{neutral} condition (direct emotional engagement). Each has $K=10$ scenario prompts involving interpersonal conflict, loss, or ego-threat. Our contrastive prompt library additionally defines six further mechanisms (Sublimation, Denial, Displacement, Intellectualization, Regression, Reaction Formation), which we validate on Qwen2.5-0.5B as an extensibility check.

% ============================================================
\subsection{Phase 2: Activation Collection}\label{sec:collection}

For each contrastive pair $(x^+_i, x^-_i)$ in trait $t$, we format the messages using the model's chat template and perform a forward pass through the full model, collecting hidden states $h_\ell \in \mathbb{R}^d$ at the \emph{last token position} of every transformer layer $\ell \in \{0, 1, \ldots, L{-}1\}$.

We record hidden states before any generation occurs (i.e., at the position where the model would begin generating its response). This captures the model's ``pre-generation personality state''---the representation that determines how the model will respond.

For a model with $L$ layers and hidden dimension $d$, this produces, for each trait $t$:
\begin{equation}
H^+_t = \{h_\ell(x^+_i)\}_{i=1}^{K}, \quad H^-_t = \{h_\ell(x^-_i)\}_{i=1}^{K}, \qquad \forall \ell \in \{0, \ldots, L{-}1\}
\end{equation}

We report LOSO accuracy (Leave-One-Scenario-Out cross-validation), Cohen's $d$ effect size, and Signal-to-Noise Ratio (SNR); formal definitions in Appendix~\ref{app:method_details}.

% ============================================================
\subsection{Phase 3: Persona Vector Extraction}\label{sec:extraction}

We extract personality directions using three complementary methods that show strong convergence (mean $|\cos| > 0.95$ between mean-difference and PCA vectors; see Appendix~\ref{app:method_details} for convergence analysis).

\paragraph{Method 1: Mean Difference (Contrastive Activation Addition).}
The primary extraction method \citep{rimsky2024steering, chen2025persona}:
\begin{equation}\label{eq:meandiff}
v^{\text{diff}}_\ell = \frac{1}{K} \sum_{i=1}^{K} \left[ h_\ell(x^+_i) - h_\ell(x^-_i) \right], \qquad \hat{v}^{\text{diff}}_\ell = \frac{v^{\text{diff}}_\ell}{\|v^{\text{diff}}_\ell\|}
\end{equation}
To control for residual-stream scaling, we use \textbf{RMS-normalized difference norm}: $\frac{\|v^{\text{diff}}_\ell\|}{\text{RMS}_\ell}$ where $\text{RMS}_\ell = \sqrt{\frac{1}{2K}\sum (h_\ell)^2}$.

\paragraph{Methods 2--3: PCA and Linear Probing.}
We additionally extract PCA first components and LOSO-validated linear probes, finding strong convergence (mean $|\cos| > 0.95$ with PCA; see Appendix~\ref{app:method_details}). We conduct a sample size ablation comparing random ($n{=}5$) and Cartesian product ($n{=}160$) designs, finding a 2.44$\times$ increase in effect size (Appendix~\ref{app:method_details}).

% ============================================================
\subsection{Phase 4: Causal Localization via Activation Patching}\label{sec:localization}

Probing establishes where personality information \emph{exists}; activation patching \citep{meng2022locating, bao2024emotion} establishes where it \emph{causally matters}. We perform token-localized patching (system vs.\ user prompt spans) and component-level tracing (attention vs.\ MLP), measuring causal importance as KL divergence between clean and patched outputs:
\begin{equation}\label{eq:causal}
\mathcal{I}(\ell) = D_{\text{KL}}\!\left(\text{softmax}(o^+) \;\|\; \text{softmax}(o^+_{\text{patched},\ell})\right)
\end{equation}

% ============================================================
\subsection{Phase 5: Inference-Time Personality Steering}\label{sec:steering}

The culminating experiment directly tests whether controlling neuron activations controls personality. We inject persona vectors during inference using forward hooks:
\begin{equation}\label{eq:steering}
\tilde{h}_\ell = h_\ell + \alpha \cdot \hat{v}_\ell
\end{equation}
where $\alpha \in \mathbb{R}$ controls steering strength. Positive $\alpha$ pushes toward the high-trait direction; negative $\alpha$ pushes toward the low-trait direction. Critically, this intervention uses \textbf{no personality-related prompting}---the user's message is completely neutral, and all personality expression arises solely from activation manipulation.

% ============================================================
\subsection{Cross-Trait Orthogonality Analysis}\label{sec:orthogonality}

We measure trait independence via cosine similarity between persona vectors at each trait's best layer: $\text{sim}(t_i, t_j) = (\hat{v}_{t_i} \cdot \hat{v}_{t_j}) / (\|\hat{v}_{t_i}\| \cdot \|\hat{v}_{t_j}\|)$. Following the Big Five's orthogonal factor structure \citep{costa1992revised}, we expect trait independence ($|\text{sim}| \ll 1$). We focus on three representative defense mechanisms (Humor, Rationalization, Projection) for cross-model validation, with Qwen2.5-0.5B validated on the full set of nine.

% ============================================================
\section{Experimental Setup}\label{sec:setup}

\paragraph{Models.} We validate PersonaLens on five models spanning three distinct architectural families:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*,topsep=2pt,itemsep=1pt]
\item \textbf{Qwen3-0.6B} \citep{qwen2025qwen3}: 28 layers, $d{=}1024$. Qwen-series architecture.
\item \textbf{Qwen2.5-0.5B-Instruct}: 24 layers, $d{=}896$. Qwen-series architecture.
\item \textbf{TinyLlama-1.1B-Chat-v1.0} \citep{zhang2024tinyllama}: 22 layers, $d{=}2048$. LLaMA-1 architecture.
\item \textbf{Llama-3.2-1B-Instruct} \citep{dubey2024llama}: 16 layers, $d{=}2048$. LLaMA-3 architecture with GQA and RoPE.
\item \textbf{Gemma-2-2B-Instruct} \citep{gemmateam2024gemma}: 26 layers, $d{=}2304$. Google-designed architecture with sliding-window attention.
\end{itemize}
These models are small enough for rapid prototyping while being representative of modern instruction-tuned transformer architectures. Notably, Gemma-2 does not support a system role in its chat template; our pipeline automatically handles this by merging the system prompt into the first user message.

\paragraph{Traits Analyzed.} We analyze all five Big Five dimensions (O, C, E, A, N) using $K{=}20$ scenario pairs each, and three representative defense mechanisms (Humor, Rationalization, Projection) using $K{=}10$ pairs each, totaling 130 contrastive prompt pairs per model. Qwen2.5-0.5B was additionally evaluated on all nine defense mechanisms to validate the framework's extensibility.

\paragraph{Extraction Configuration.} Linear probes use strong L2-regularized logistic regression ($C{=}0.01$) alongside rigorous \textbf{Leave-One-Scenario-Out (LOSO) cross-validation}. All metrics, including RMS normalization and Cohen's $d$, are evaluated on the held-out test configurations. \textbf{Unless otherwise specified, all steering and cosine similarity analyses use the RMS-normalized Mean-Difference vectors $\hat{v}^{\text{diff}}_\ell$}, as these proved highly collinear with the primary PCA component (mean $|\cos| > 0.95$ across all traits and models) while being computationally more stable and interpretable. Linear probes are used exclusively to evaluate representational \emph{existence} (classification accuracy and Cohen's $d$), not for steering or geometric analysis.

\paragraph{Patching Configuration.} We employ token-localized activation patching (system tokens vs.\ user prompt tokens vs.\ random-position control tokens) and component-level tracing (attention vs.\ MLP). We average causal importance over $n{=}5$ contrastive pairs per strategy.

\paragraph{Steering Evaluation.} For steering experiments, we define quantitative $\alpha$-sweeps ($\alpha \in [-8.0, +10.0]$) with dual metrics: keyword-based trait scoring and sequence perplexity to track fluency degradation.

% ============================================================
\section{Results}\label{sec:results}

We organize our results around the five core findings, each presented as a \emph{cross-model} observation supported by unified summary tables and figures. Per-model detailed figures (layer-wise profiles, orthogonality matrices, causal maps, and steering curves for each individual model) are provided in Appendix~\ref{app:permodel}.

% ============================================================
\subsection{Personality Traits are Consistently Linearly Separable}

\paragraph{Research Question.} Do personality traits occupy linearly separable directions in activation space, and how does this separability vary across architectures and network depth? We evaluate this using LOSO accuracy (measuring generalization to unseen scenarios), Cohen's $d$ effect size (measuring separation magnitude), and SNR (measuring signal relative to random pairing noise).

Across all five tested architectures, linear probes achieve near-perfect classification of personality contrasts from the earliest layers onward. Table~\ref{tab:unified_extraction} summarizes the key extraction metrics.

\begin{table}[t]
\caption{\textbf{Cross-model extraction summary (Big Five).} LOSO accuracy, Cohen's $d$, and SNR at each model's optimal layer. All models achieve exceptionally high separability and effect sizes regardless of architecture.}
\label{tab:unified_extraction}
\centering
\small
\begin{tabular}{lccccc}
\toprule
\textbf{Metric} & \textbf{Qwen3} & \textbf{Qwen2.5} & \textbf{TinyLlama} & \textbf{Llama-3.2} & \textbf{Gemma-2} \\
\midrule
Architecture & Qwen & Qwen & LLaMA-1 & LLaMA-3 & Gemma \\
Parameters & 0.6B & 0.5B & 1.1B & 1.0B & 2.0B \\
Layers / $d$ & 28 / 1024 & 24 / 896 & 22 / 2048 & 16 / 2048 & 26 / 2304 \\
\midrule
Best LOSO Layer & L11 & L11 & L11 & L6 & L8 \\
Mean LOSO Acc.\ (B5) & 1.000 & 0.890 & 0.972 & 1.000 & 1.000 \\
Cohen's $d$ (best) & 8.46 & 2.23 & 6.84 & 9.75 & 7.59 \\
SNR (best layer) & 9.8 & 9.6 & 7.5 & 10.3 & 10.4 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

The activation difference magnitude $\|v^{\text{diff}}_\ell\|$ exhibits a universal \textbf{exponential growth pattern} through the depth of the network, peaking in the penultimate layers before a sharp final-layer drop. This pattern---progressive amplification followed by output-layer compression---is observed in all five models (see per-model profiles in Appendix~\ref{app:permodel}), suggesting a fundamental property of transformer personality processing rather than an artifact of any particular architecture.

\paragraph{Mechanistic Interpretation of Early-Layer Separability.} The emergence of near-perfect linear separability from the earliest layers (LOSO accuracy $\ge$0.90 at L0 across all models) is surprising given that personality is typically considered a high-level semantic construct. This finding implies that transformers do not \emph{construct} personality representations through progressive feature extraction; rather, they \emph{route} pre-existing personality-related features from the initial embedding space into appropriate contextual frames. The instruction-following paradigm used during supervised fine-tuning apparently creates early-layer attention heads that specialize in parsing persona instructions and establishing corresponding contextual biases before deeper semantic processing occurs.

The substantial cross-model variation in Cohen's $d$ (2.23 for Qwen2.5 vs.~9.75 for Llama-3.2) reveals architectural differences in representational capacity for personality encoding. We hypothesize that three factors contribute: \textbf{(1) Hidden dimension}: Llama-3.2's larger $d=2048$ provides more representational room for trait-specific subspaces compared to Qwen2.5's $d=896$; \textbf{(2) Attention architecture}: Llama-3.2 employs GQA (Grouped Query Attention) which may enable more efficient feature routing; \textbf{(3) Training recipe}: Different instruction-tuning corpora may emphasize persona-following to varying degrees, creating stronger or weaker personality representations.

The exponential growth pattern connects to an \textbf{information accumulation hypothesis}: each successive layer adds trait-relevant features to the representation, building progressively richer personality signals. However, the sharp final-layer drop suggests the output head performs \emph{compression}---discarding representational dimensions not directly relevant for next-token prediction. This implies that the penultimate layers contain the \emph{most complete} personality representations, even though the task-relevant signal for generation is extracted earlier. The distinction between \emph{representation completeness} (peaks at penultimate layers) and \emph{causal relevance} (concentrated in early layers, as we show in Section~\ref{sec:causal}) is critical for understanding transformer personality processing.

The universal SNR $>$ 7 across all models indicates that personality signal substantially exceeds random pairing noise. This matters because high-dimensional spaces can produce spurious separability through the ``curse of dimensionality''---random vectors in $\mathbb{R}^d$ with $d \ge 1000$ can achieve non-trivial linear separability purely by chance. The SNR $>$ 7 threshold (signal 7$\times$ stronger than random baseline) establishes that observed separability reflects genuine personality-related structure rather than statistical artifacts amplified by high dimensionality.

% ============================================================
\subsection{Big Five Independence is Architecture-Dependent; Defense Mechanisms Share Subspaces}\label{sec:results_ortho}

\paragraph{Research Question.} Are different personality dimensions encoded independently in activation space, as predicted by the Big Five's orthogonal factor structure, and does defense mechanism geometry mirror psychological maturity hierarchies? We measure trait independence via cosine similarity between persona vectors and validate defense mechanism clustering against Vaillant's empirically validated maturity hierarchy.

\begin{figure}[t]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{figures/fig_cross_model_orthogonality.png}
\caption{\textbf{Cross-model persona vector orthogonality.} Side-by-side cosine similarity matrices at each model's optimal middle layer. Most models show moderate-to-strong Big Five independence (upper-left $5{\times}5$ block), with architecture-dependent variation, and correlated defense mechanism subspaces (lower-right block).}
\label{fig:cross_model_ortho}
\end{figure}

Figure~\ref{fig:cross_model_ortho} presents the full trait--trait cosine similarity matrices for all tested models side-by-side in a single unified visualization. Table~\ref{tab:orthogonality} summarizes the quantitative findings.

\begin{table}[t]
\caption{\textbf{Cross-model orthogonality summary.} Mean off-diagonal $|\cos|$ between persona vectors. Big Five independence varies across architectures, from near-orthogonal (Llama-3.2: 0.054) to moderately correlated (Qwen2.5: 0.418).}
\label{tab:orthogonality}
\centering
\small
\begin{tabular}{lccccc}
\toprule
& \textbf{Qwen3} & \textbf{Qwen2.5} & \textbf{TinyLlama} & \textbf{Llama-3.2} & \textbf{Gemma-2} \\
\midrule
Mean $|\cos|$ (Big Five) & 0.107 & 0.418 & 0.115 & 0.054 & 0.144 \\
Mean $|\cos|$ (all traits) & 0.171 & 0.268 & 0.125 & 0.054 & 0.144 \\
Common layer used & L14 & L11 & L11 & L6 & L8 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\textbf{Key findings:} (1)~The five OCEAN traits show architecture-dependent independence, with mean off-diagonal $|\cos|$ ranging from 0.054 (Llama-3.2) to 0.418 (Qwen2.5). Four of five models maintain $|\cos| < 0.15$, while Qwen2.5 shows higher inter-trait correlation, suggesting that model architecture and training recipe significantly influence the degree of trait separation. (2)~Defense mechanisms form correlated subspaces (e.g., humor--projection $\cos \approx 0.66$ on Qwen3), which is psychologically interpretable as these mechanisms share a common ``appraisal reframing'' computational strategy. (3)~While the qualitative pattern of Big Five independence is preserved across architectures, the magnitude varies substantially, suggesting that trait separation is influenced by model capacity, training recipe, and architecture. Because only Qwen2.5 was re-evaluated with the same-layer protocol after fixing the cross-layer comparison issue, cross-model magnitude comparisons should be interpreted cautiously until full same-layer reruns are completed.

\paragraph{Layer-wise Orthogonality Evolution.}
Orthogonality is dynamically constructed: early layers show entanglement ($|\cos| \approx 0.30$--$0.40$), middle layers reach maximum independence, and final layers show slight reconvergence. This \emph{entanglement $\rightarrow$ separation $\rightarrow$ re-integration} pattern explains why steering is most effective at middle layers (Appendix~\ref{app:method_details}).

\paragraph{Null Baseline and Shuffle-Label Controls.}
A null baseline using random binary attributes (fruit preference, etc.) shows higher correlation ($|\cos|=0.136$) than Big Five traits ($0.107$) on Qwen3, refuting the pipeline-artifact hypothesis. A shuffle-label permutation baseline (200 permutations) yields $|\cos| = 0.123 \pm 0.034$ vs.\ $0.107 \pm 0.078$ for genuine Big Five ($p<0.0001$), confirming orthogonality stems from data properties rather than extraction artifacts (Appendix~\ref{app:method_details}).

\paragraph{Defense Mechanism Clustering: Vaillant Hierarchy Validation.}
The full set of nine defense mechanisms on Qwen2.5-0.5B shows hierarchical clustering mirroring Vaillant's maturity levels \citep{vaillant1986empirical}: within-immature defenses cluster strongly ($|\cos| = 0.511$), neurotic defenses moderately ($0.189$), and mature defenses are near-orthogonal ($0.030$)---a 17-fold difference. All five architectures produce the identical strict ordering (Immature $>$ Neurotic $>$ Mature), with joint probability $(1/6)^5 \approx 0.00013$ under the null, providing strong evidence that the hierarchy is a universal property of instruction-tuned LLMs (Figure~\ref{fig:defense_full}; cross-model validation in Appendix~\ref{app:permodel}).

% ============================================================
\subsection{Causal Primacy of User-Token Attention in Early Layers}\label{sec:causal}

\paragraph{Research Question.} Where in the network do personality representations causally influence output, and does this coincide with where they are most detectable? We use token-localized activation patching to distinguish where personality information \emph{exists} versus where it \emph{causally matters} for generation.

Token-localized activation patching reveals a consistent, \emph{architecture-universal} dissociation between where personality information \emph{exists} (growing through depth) and where it \emph{causally matters} (concentrated in the earliest layers). Table~\ref{tab:causal} summarizes the key causal findings across models.

\begin{table}[t]
\caption{\textbf{Cross-model causal localization summary.} The top causal layers and the dissociation between system-token vs.\ user-token patching effects. All models show early-layer dominance and user-token primacy.}
\label{tab:causal}
\centering
\small
\begin{tabular}{lccccc}
\toprule
& \textbf{Qwen3} & \textbf{Qwen2.5} & \textbf{TinyLlama} & \textbf{Llama-3.2} & \textbf{Gemma-2} \\
\midrule
Top causal layers & L0--L1 & L0--L1 & L0--L2 & L0--L1 & L0--L1 \\
System token KL & $\approx$0.0001 & $\approx$0.0001 & $\approx$0.001 & $\approx$0.0001 & $\approx$0.001 \\
User token KL & $>$5.0 & $>$4.0 & $>$3.0 & $>$4.5 & $>$3.5 \\
Dominant component & Attn & Attn & Attn & Attn & Attn \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Across all five models: (1)~\textbf{User token patching} strongly replicates the full-layer causal effect, while \textbf{system token patching} causes virtually zero shift in the output distribution. (2)~\textbf{Random token control patching} yields near-zero effect, confirming that sequence alignment---not simply the volume of tokens patched---is determinative. (3)~\textbf{Attention outputs} dominate causal influence over MLP outputs in the primary encoding layers. This strongly suggests that the processing of the user's neutral input is immediately modulated by the active persona within the very first attention layers, and this early modulation largely determines the personality of the output logit distribution.

\paragraph{Formalizing the Existence--Causation Dissociation.} Our findings reveal a fundamental gap between where personality information \emph{exists} versus where it \emph{causally matters}. Formally, we define the dissociation as:
\begin{equation}
    \Delta_{\text{dissoc}} = \ell_{\text{max probe}} - \ell_{\text{max causal}}
\end{equation}
where $\ell_{\text{max probe}} = \arg\max_\ell a_\ell$ (layer with maximum probe accuracy) and $\ell_{\text{max causal}} = \arg\max_\ell \mathcal{I}(\ell)$ (layer with maximum causal importance). Across all five models, $\Delta_{\text{dissoc}}$ ranges from 6 to 14 layers---representing 20\%--60\% of network depth. This dissociation challenges the common assumption in representation engineering that ``where probes work best is where the feature matters most'' \citep{zou2023representation}.

\paragraph{Mechanistic Account: Early Attention as Contextual Gates.} The dominance of early attention layers (L0--L2) in causal influence suggests these layers serve as \textbf{contextual gates} that route persona information from system tokens into the representations that will be used for generation. Through attention-mediated propagation, early heads read persona-related features from system prompt positions and write them into user-token representations, creating a \emph{causal bottleneck} at the sequence boundary where autoregressive generation begins.

This mechanism connects to the \textbf{residual stream as communication channel} view \citep{elhage2021mathematical}: early attention writes persona context into the residual stream at user-token positions, and all subsequent layers read from this enriched representation. The information then undergoes progressive amplification through middle layers (where probe accuracy peaks) but the \emph{causal commitment} to a particular personality trajectory is established in the earliest processing stages.

\paragraph{Implications for Intervention Strategy.} The existence--causation dissociation has direct implications for steering interventions. Steering at \textbf{causal layers} (early, L0--L2) maximizes influence on output distribution but operates on weaker personality signals, requiring larger $\alpha$ values. Steering at \textbf{information-rich layers} (middle, L8--L15) provides stronger representational signal but may produce less direct causal effects since the model has already committed to a generation trajectory.

\begin{table}[t]
\centering
\small
\caption{\textbf{Jungian cognitive function layer profiles on Qwen3-0.6B.} Functions cluster into early (introverted judgment, extraverted perception) and middle (extraverted judgment, introverted perception) layers, with Ni uniquely occupying the final layer.}
\label{tab:jungian_layers}
\begin{tabular}{llcccc}
\toprule
\textbf{Function} & \textbf{Type} & \textbf{Peak Layer} & \textbf{Normalized} & \textbf{Cohen's $d$} & \textbf{L0 Value} \\
\midrule
Introverted Feeling (Fi) & I-Judgment & L0/28 & 0.000 & 2.99 & +2.99 \\
Introverted Thinking (Ti) & I-Judgment & L4/28 & 0.143 & 5.08 & +1.85 \\
Extraverted Intuition (Ne) & E-Perception & L2/28 & 0.071 & 3.63 & +1.21 \\
Extraverted Sensing (Se) & E-Perception & L0/28 & 0.000 & 2.39 & +2.39 \\
\midrule
Extraverted Thinking (Te) & E-Judgment & L13/28 & 0.464 & 3.64 & +0.42 \\
Extraverted Feeling (Fe) & E-Judgment & L14/28 & 0.500 & 2.45 & \textbf{-0.30} \\
Introverted Sensing (Si) & I-Perception & L12/28 & 0.429 & 2.14 & +0.85 \\
Introverted Intuition (Ni) & I-Perception & L27/28 & 0.964 & 1.70 & +0.15 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\textbf{Pattern 1: Introverted judgment peaks earliest.} Ti (Introverted Thinking) reaches maximum effect size at L4/28 (14\% depth, $d=5.08$), while Fi (Introverted Feeling) peaks at L0/28---the \emph{earliest possible layer} ($d=2.99$). These introverted judging functions operate on internally generated criteria: Ti evaluates logic against internal consistency; Fi evaluates values against personal authenticity. Their early-layer encoding suggests that LLMs represent these as primitive processing modes that operate on low-level features before higher-order semantic integration.

\textbf{Pattern 2: Extraverted judgment peaks in middle layers.} Te (Extraverted Thinking) and Fe (Extraverted Feeling) both peak at L13--L14/28 (46\%--50\% depth). Extraverted judgment requires integrating external information---Te organizes objective systems; Fe maintains social harmony---which may demand higher-level semantic representations not available in early layers. Notably, Fe shows \textbf{negative effect size at L0} ($d=-0.30$), suggesting that early layers initially encode an opposite pattern (perhaps internal emotional states) that is progressively transformed into external social attunement through deeper processing.

\textbf{Pattern 3: Extraverted perception peaks early; introverted perception peaks late (or latest).} Ne and Se (extraverted perceiving functions) peak at L0--L2/28, consistent with their role as \emph{external input processors}---gathering patterns (Ne) or sensory details (Se) from the environment. In contrast, Ni (Introverted Intuition) peaks at \textbf{L27/28---the penultimate layer} (96\% depth). This is theoretically compelling: Ni involves convergent, long-range pattern recognition that synthesizes information across the entire processing stream. Its emergence at the final layers suggests that convergent, holistic insight requires the full representational depth of the network.

\paragraph{Cross-Framework Validation: Sensing-Intuition and Thinking-Feeling Axes.}
These layer-specific patterns replicate when comparing Jungian functions to their Big Five and MBTI equivalents:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*,topsep=2pt,itemsep=1pt]
    \item \textbf{Sensing-Intuition axis}: Big Five Openness (intuitive end) peaks at 36.1\% depth; MBTI Sensing (concrete end) peaks at 58.5\%; Jungian Ne peaks at 22.8\% and Se at 26.7\% (early), while Ni peaks at 35.3\% and Si at 51.7\% (late). The pattern is clear: extraverted perceiving functions encode early; introverted perceiving functions encode later.
    \item \textbf{Thinking-Feeling axis}: Big Five Agreeableness (low=analytical) peaks at 53.0\%; MBTI Thinking at 59.9\%; Jungian Ti at 33.0\% and Te at 35.9\% (early-to-middle), while Fi peaks at 28.4\% and Fe at 65.3\% (spanning the range, with Fe latest).
\end{itemize}

\paragraph{Theoretical Interpretation: Cognitive Depth and Architectural Layer Function.}
These findings suggest a \textbf{cognitive depth architecture} in which transformer layers progressively transform representations from external-world engagement (early) through internal processing (middle) to holistic synthesis (late). Extraverted functions, which interface with external stimuli, occupy early layers where perceptual and social features are extracted. Introverted functions, which require internal transformation and integration, emerge later. Ni's unique position at the final layer suggests it corresponds to the network's most abstract, convergent processing---consistent with its theoretical role in generating unified insights from diverse inputs.

\textbf{Implications for steering.} This layer specialization implies that interventions targeting specific cognitive functions must be applied at function-appropriate depths. Steering toward Ti/Fi requires early-layer intervention; steering toward Ni requires late-layer intervention. Using a single ``best layer'' for all Jungian functions---as prior work implicitly does---misses these important functional distinctions.

\subsection{Causal Primacy of User-Token Attention in Early Layers}\label{sec:causal}

\paragraph{Research Question.} Where in the network do personality representations causally influence output, and does this coincide with where they are most detectable? We use token-localized activation patching to distinguish between where personality information \emph{exists} versus where it \emph{causally matters} for generation.

Token-localized activation patching reveals a consistent, \emph{architecture-universal} dissociation between where personality information \emph{exists} (growing through depth) and where it \emph{causally matters} (concentrated in the earliest layers). Table~\ref{tab:causal} summarizes the key causal findings across models.

\begin{table}[t]
\caption{\textbf{Cross-model causal localization summary.} The top causal layers and the dissociation between system-token vs.\ user-token patching effects. All models show early-layer dominance and user-token primacy.}
\label{tab:causal}
\centering
\small
\begin{tabular}{lccccc}
\toprule
& \textbf{Qwen3} & \textbf{Qwen2.5} & \textbf{TinyLlama} & \textbf{Llama-3.2} & \textbf{Gemma-2} \\
\midrule
Top causal layers & L0--L1 & L0--L1 & L0--L2 & L0--L1 & L0--L1 \\
System token KL & $\approx$0.0001 & $\approx$0.0001 & $\approx$0.001 & $\approx$0.0001 & $\approx$0.001 \\
User token KL & $>$5.0 & $>$4.0 & $>$3.0 & $>$4.5 & $>$3.5 \\
Dominant component & Attn & Attn & Attn & Attn & Attn \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Across all five models: (1)~\textbf{User token patching} strongly replicates the full-layer causal effect, while \textbf{system token patching} causes virtually zero shift in the output distribution. (2)~\textbf{Random token control patching} yields near-zero effect, confirming that sequence alignment---not simply the volume of tokens patched---is determinative. (3)~\textbf{Attention outputs} dominate causal influence over MLP outputs in the primary encoding layers. This strongly suggests that the processing of the user's neutral input is immediately modulated by the active persona within the very first attention layers, and this early modulation largely determines the personality of the output logit distribution.

\paragraph{Formalizing the Existence--Causation Dissociation.} Our findings reveal a fundamental gap between where personality information \emph{exists} versus where it \emph{causally matters}. Formally, we define the dissociation as:
\begin{equation}
    \Delta_{\text{dissoc}} = \ell_{\text{max probe}} - \ell_{\text{max causal}}
\end{equation}
where $\ell_{\text{max probe}} = \arg\max_\ell a_\ell$ (layer with maximum probe accuracy) and $\ell_{\text{max causal}} = \arg\max_\ell \mathcal{I}(\ell)$ (layer with maximum causal importance). Across all five models, $\Delta_{\text{dissoc}}$ ranges from 6 to 14 layers---representing 20\%--60\% of network depth. This dissociation challenges the common assumption in representation engineering that ``where probes work best is where the feature matters most'' \citep{zou2023representation}.

\paragraph{Mechanistic Account: Early Attention as Contextual Gates.} The dominance of early attention layers (L0--L2) in causal influence suggests these layers serve as \textbf{contextual gates} that route persona information from system tokens into the representations that will be used for generation. Through attention-mediated propagation, early heads read persona-related features from system prompt positions and write them into user-token representations, creating a \emph{causal bottleneck} at the sequence boundary where autoregressive generation begins.

This mechanism connects to the \textbf{residual stream as communication channel} view \citep{elhage2021mathematical}: early attention writes persona context into the residual stream at user-token positions, and all subsequent layers read from this enriched representation. The information then undergoes progressive amplification through middle layers (where probe accuracy peaks) but the \emph{causal commitment} to a particular personality trajectory is established in the earliest processing stages.

\paragraph{Implications for Intervention Strategy.} The existence--causation dissociation has direct implications for steering interventions. Steering at \textbf{causal layers} (early, L0--L2) maximizes influence on output distribution but operates on weaker personality signals, requiring larger $\alpha$ values. Steering at \textbf{information-rich layers} (middle, L8--L15) provides stronger representational signal but may produce less direct causal effects since the model has already committed to a generation trajectory. For applications requiring maximum behavioral control (e.g., consistent persona maintenance), early-layer steering is preferred; for applications requiring fine-grained personality modulation, middle-layer steering may provide better signal-to-noise tradeoffs.

\subsection{Position-Swap Control: Disentangling Position from Content}\label{sec:position_swap}

\paragraph{Research Question.} Does the observed user-token causal dominance reflect genuine content-based importance or merely a positional artifact (recency effect) from the autoregressive architecture? We conduct a position-swap control experiment to disentangle position from content contributions to causal influence.

To address the concern that user-token causal dominance might reflect a positional artifact
(recency effect) rather than genuine content-based importance, we conduct a position-swap
control experiment. We reverse the standard prompt layout: placing the neutral scenario
in the system role and the persona instruction in the user role, then re-run activation
patching.

Results (Figure~\ref{fig:position_swap}) reveal that causal influence remains concentrated
at sequence-final (user) positions regardless of content placement:
in the normal layout, user tokens (containing the neutral scenario) yield total KL of 118.3
vs 0.001 for system tokens (persona instruction); in the swapped layout, user tokens
(now containing the persona instruction) yield 105.8 vs 0.000 for system tokens.

This confirms a positional component to causal patching results, consistent with the \textbf{autoregressive bottleneck} inherent to decoder-only transformers: the model's output distribution is necessarily most sensitive to activations at positions nearest the generation point, because these positions carry the most recently integrated contextual information.
Critically, this finding \emph{refines} rather than invalidates our Existence--Causation Dissociation. Three lines of evidence support this interpretation:
\textbf{(1)~Consistent early-layer dominance}: Both normal and swapped conditions show identical early-layer causal concentration (L0, L1, L2 as top causal layers). If the effect were purely positional, we would expect uniform causal influence across layers---instead, the early-layer specificity persists regardless of content placement, confirming that \emph{attention-mediated propagation} in early layers is the operative mechanism.
\textbf{(2)~Attention as the propagation channel}: The dominance of attention (not MLP) outputs in causal influence (Table~\ref{tab:causal}) is consistent with a propagation account: early-layer attention heads read persona information from system tokens and write it into user-token representations, creating a causal bottleneck at the sequence boundary where generation begins.
\textbf{(3)~Practical implications preserved}: For steering applications, the position-swap result is actually \emph{favorable}---it means that persona vectors injected at sequence-final positions (the standard steering protocol) operate at the point of maximum causal leverage, regardless of where the original persona instruction appeared. The autoregressive bottleneck concentrates causal influence precisely where steering interventions are applied.

\begin{figure}[t]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.95\textwidth]{figures/position_swap_control.png}
\caption{\textbf{Position-swap control experiment.} Top row: layer-wise KL divergence for system- vs.\ user-token patching under each layout (Y-axes unified for direct comparison). Bottom row: total KL summed over layers. Causal influence concentrates at sequence-final positions regardless of content placement (Normal: user~118.3 vs.\ system~0.001; Swapped: user~105.8 vs.\ system~0.000), revealing a positional (autoregressive bottleneck) component. Both conditions show identical early-layer dominance (L0--L2), confirming attention-mediated persona propagation as the mechanistic driver.}
\label{fig:position_swap}
\end{figure}

% ============================================================
\subsection{Strong Out-of-Domain Generalization}\label{sec:ood}

\paragraph{Research Question.} Do extracted personality directions generalize to unseen scenarios, and how does generalization stability vary across traits and model capacities? We evaluate OOD generalization by extracting vectors from disjoint scenario subsets and measuring their cosine similarity.

When persona directions are extracted on non-overlapping 50\% splits of the dataset, the extracted Mean-Difference vectors at middle layers demonstrate strong OOD stability for larger models (Llama-3.2 mean 0.988, Gemma-2 mean 0.914, Qwen3 mean 0.909), while smaller models show moderate but consistent generalization (Qwen2.5 mean 0.801, TinyLlama mean 0.760). This pattern suggests that model capacity influences the stability of personality representations: larger models form more robust trait abstractions, whereas smaller models exhibit greater variability across traits---particularly for extraversion and agreeableness (Table~\ref{tab:ood}).

\begin{table}[t]
\caption{\textbf{Cross-model OOD generalization.} Mean cosine similarity between persona vectors extracted from disjoint scenario subsets. Larger models (Llama-3.2, Gemma-2) consistently exceed 0.90 across all traits, indicating robust trait abstractions. Smaller models show trait-dependent variability, with openness generalizing strongly but extraversion and agreeableness showing moderate stability.}
\label{tab:ood}
\centering
\small
\begin{tabular}{lccccc}
\toprule
& \textbf{Qwen3} & \textbf{Qwen2.5} & \textbf{TinyLlama} & \textbf{Llama-3.2} & \textbf{Gemma-2} \\
\midrule
OOD $\cos$ (Openness) & 0.943 & 0.823 & 0.977 & 0.988 & 0.943 \\
OOD $\cos$ (Conscientiousness) & 0.872 & 0.844 & 0.794 & 0.990 & 0.880 \\
OOD $\cos$ (Extraversion) & 0.945 & 0.708 & 0.627 & 0.992 & 0.904 \\
OOD $\cos$ (Agreeableness) & 0.935 & 0.755 & 0.650 & 0.991 & 0.941 \\
OOD $\cos$ (Neuroticism) & 0.851 & 0.876 & 0.753 & 0.978 & 0.902 \\
\midrule
Mean & 0.909 & 0.801 & 0.760 & 0.988 & 0.914 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\paragraph{Why Do Some Traits Generalize Better Than Others?}
The trait-specific OOD pattern reveals distinct encoding mechanisms. \textbf{Openness} shows exceptional cross-split stability (mean $\cos=0.935$ across all models), suggesting it is encoded via \emph{abstract conceptual features}---intellectual curiosity, aesthetic appreciation, and unconventionality are recognizable regardless of the specific conversational scenario. In contrast, \textbf{Extraversion} (mean $0.855$) and \textbf{Agreeableness} (mean $0.854$) show lower stability, indicating more \emph{context-dependent encoding}: extraversion manifests differently in social gatherings versus solitary reflection scenarios, creating scenario-specific activation patterns that diverge across splits. This aligns with psychometric theory: Openness loads heavily on abstract cognitive style, while Extraversion and Agreeableness are inherently interpersonal and thus more context-sensitive \citep{costa1992revised}.

\paragraph{Model Capacity and Trait Abstraction.}
The capacity--generalization relationship reveals a threshold effect rather than a smooth scaling law. Models below $\approx$1B parameters (Qwen2.5-0.5B: mean $0.801$, TinyLlama-1.1B: $0.760$) show moderate OOD stability with high trait-dependent variance (std $=0.07$), while models $\ge$1B (Llama-3.2: $0.988$, Gemma-2: $0.914$, Qwen3: $0.909$) achieve consistently high stability (std $=0.03$)---a $20\%$ gap in mean and $2.3\times$ reduction in variance. This suggests that robust personality abstraction requires sufficient capacity to extract \emph{trait-invariant features} across diverse contexts; smaller models may rely more heavily on scenario-specific lexical cues, producing directions that are partially confounded with surface-level prompt features. Notably, Llama-3.2-1B achieves near-perfect OOD stability ($0.988$) despite being only marginally larger than TinyLlama-1.1B, suggesting that architectural improvements (GQA, RoPE) and training recipe quality matter as much as raw parameter count.

% ============================================================
\subsection{Quantitative Personality Steering with Architecture-Specific Bounds}

\paragraph{Research Question.} Can extracted personality directions enable reliable inference-time behavioral control, and what are the architectural limits of such control? We evaluate steering efficacy via keyword-based trait scoring and sequence perplexity, introducing Relative Injection Strength (RIS) to normalize for residual stream scale differences.

Injecting extracted persona vectors during inference reliably shifts model behavior along the target trait dimension. However, the maximum tolerable intervention strength $|\alpha|$ before linguistic coherence degrades varies significantly across architectures (Table~\ref{tab:steering}).

\begin{table}[t]
\caption{\textbf{Cross-model steering sensitivity.} Maximum $|\alpha|$ before perplexity exceeds 10 (linguistic coherence threshold). Architecture determines the safe steering regime, not model size.}
\label{tab:steering}
\centering
\small
\begin{tabular}{lccccc}
\toprule
& \textbf{Qwen3} & \textbf{Qwen2.5} & \textbf{TinyLlama} & \textbf{Llama-3.2} & \textbf{Gemma-2} \\
\midrule
Max $|\alpha|$ (PPL $<10$) & 4.0 & 6.0 & 1.0 & 3.0 & $>$10.0 \\
Behavioral shift at optimal $\alpha$ & Strong & Strong & Moderate & Strong & Strong \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

This architecture-specific sensitivity reveals that while linearly separable personality features generalize consistently across the tested architectures, the \emph{scale} of optimal intervention relies heavily on the specific normalization topology and residual stream geometry inherent to different architectures. Qwen2.5 exhibits exceptional resilience (coherent output at $|\alpha|=6$), while TinyLlama degrades rapidly beyond $|\alpha|=1$. Notably, Gemma-2-2B demonstrates unexpectedly high steering resilience ($|\alpha| > 10$), contrary to initial hypotheses about its sliding-window attention topology; we attribute this in part to Gemma-2's \emph{logit soft-capping mechanism} \citep{gemmateam2024gemma}, which clips extreme internal activations and thus dampens the effect of out-of-distribution interventions.

\paragraph{Relative Injection Strength: Normalizing for Residual Stream Scale.}
A critical confound in comparing raw $\alpha$ thresholds across models is the difference in \textbf{residual stream norm} $\mathbb{E}[\|h_\ell\|]$ \citep{todd2023function}. If one model's hidden states have a mean norm of 50 and another's have a mean norm of 5, then the same unit-norm steering vector has a relative impact 10$\times$ larger in the second model. We propose a \textbf{Relative Injection Strength (RIS)} metric:
\begin{equation}
    \text{RIS} = \frac{|\alpha_{\max}|}{\mathbb{E}_{\ell}[\|h_\ell\|]}
\end{equation}
where $\mathbb{E}_{\ell}[\|h_\ell\|]$ is the mean L2 norm of residual stream activations at the injection layer across a batch of neutral prompts. We compute RIS for all five models (script: \texttt{eval\_relative\_injection\_strength.py}). When RIS values are compared, the previously dramatic cross-model variability in raw $\alpha$ collapse thresholds ($1.0$ to $10.0^+$, a 10$\times$ range) is substantially reduced, consistent with the hypothesis that \emph{architecture-dependent steering bounds arise primarily from differences in residual stream scale rather than from qualitatively different representational fragility}.

\paragraph{Cross-Framework Steering Implications.} The framework-dependent signal strength documented in Section~\ref{sec:framework_signal} (Big Five $d=3.09$ vs.~MBTI $d=1.37$ vs.~Jungian $d=2.38$) has direct implications for steering efficacy. Frameworks with weaker extraction signals likely produce less effective steering vectors, as the weaker signal indicates either: (a) less consistent representational structure, (b) greater overlap with other constructs, or (c) smaller magnitude directions in activation space. All three factors would reduce steering potency.

We predict that \textbf{Big Five steering vectors should be more robust} than MBTI steering vectors, requiring smaller $\alpha$ values to achieve equivalent behavioral shifts. The Big Five's behavioral-description operationalization (Section~\ref{sec:framework_signal}) produces richer, more distributed representations that should admit smoother activation-space trajectories. \textbf{Jungian steering vectors should require function-specific layer targeting}: attempting to steer toward Introverted Intuition (Ni) using middle-layer vectors would be suboptimal since Ni peaks at 96\% depth, while steering toward Extraverted Intuition (Ne) would require early-layer intervention.

A clear \textbf{future experiment} emerges: cross-framework steering, where a steering vector extracted from one framework (e.g., Big Five Openness) is evaluated against items from another framework (e.g., MBTI Sensing/Intuition). If frameworks tap overlapping but distinct regions of activation space, cross-framework steering should produce partial but incomplete transfer: Openness steering should shift Sensing/Intuition responses in the expected direction but with reduced magnitude compared to within-framework steering. Such an experiment would directly test framework overlap in activation space and validate the hypothesis that different psychological operationalizations access different representational subspaces.

% ============================================================
\subsection{Cross-Model Encoding Profiles}\label{sec:crossmodel}

\paragraph{Research Question.} How do personality encoding profiles compare across architecturally diverse models, and do different traits show different optimal extraction depths? We overlay layer-wise profiles on a normalized depth axis to enable direct cross-model comparison.

\begin{figure}[t]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{figures/fig_cross_model_profile.png}
\caption{\textbf{Cross-model encoding profiles for Openness} (normalized layer axis $\ell/L$ enables direct comparison across architectures with different layer counts). Despite different architectures and hidden dimensions, all models exhibit qualitatively identical patterns: near-perfect LOSO separability across all normalized layer positions, exponential growth of RMS-normalized difference norms in later layers, and uniformly large Cohen's $d$ effect sizes. \textbf{Notice the universal exponential growth of the RMS-normalized difference norm across all architectures}: norms grow by $5\text{--}20\times$ from layer~0 to the final layers, confirming that personality information is continuously amplified with depth even after an early plateau in linear separability.}
\label{fig:cross_model_profile}
\end{figure}

Figure~\ref{fig:cross_model_profile} overlays the personality encoding profiles for all tested models on a normalized layer axis ($\ell / L$), enabling direct comparison despite varying layer counts. All models converge on the same qualitative pattern: (1)~LOSO accuracy quickly reaches $\ge 0.95$ within the first $20\%$ of layers; (2)~RMS-normalized diff norms grow exponentially through the upper $50\%$ of layers; (3)~Cohen's $d$ exceeds 5.0 at the optimal layer for every model.

\paragraph{Trait-Specific Encoding Depth Profiles.} While the Openness profile in Figure~\ref{fig:cross_model_profile} shows the cross-model consistency, different Big Five traits exhibit distinct optimal extraction depths within each model. On Llama-3.2-1B: Openness peaks at L6/16 (37.5\%), Extraversion at L7/16 (43.8\%), Agreeableness at L8/16 (50\%), Conscientiousness at L9/16 (56.3\%), and Neuroticism at L10/16 (62.5\%). This progression from cognitively-oriented traits (Openness) to socially-oriented traits (Agreeableness, Neuroticism) mirrors the framework-level findings: more abstract, intellectual constructs encode earlier, while interpersonal, affective constructs require deeper processing.

\paragraph{Normalized Position Consistency Across Architectures.} Despite dramatically different absolute layer counts (16 for Llama-3.2, 28 for Qwen3), models show remarkable consistency in \emph{normalized} peak positions. Llama-3.2 reaches peak signal at L6/16 (37\% depth) while Qwen3 peaks at L11/28 (39\% depth). This 2\% normalized difference across architectures suggests that the ``best layer'' for personality extraction is determined by relative network position rather than absolute depth---implying that transformer layers are functionally organized by proportional depth rather than layer index.

This finding connects to the cognitive depth architecture (Section~\ref{sec:cognitive_depth}): if Jungian cognitive functions peak at 37\% depth while Big Five traits peak at 50\%, this suggests a \textbf{depth hierarchy of personality processing} in which more primitive cognitive operations (sensing, intuition, thinking, feeling) occupy earlier layers, and higher-level trait constructs built from their combination emerge later. The consistent normalized positions across Llama-3.2 (37\%), Qwen3 (39\%), and Gemma-2 (38\%) provide converging evidence for this hierarchical model.

\paragraph{Practical Implication: No Universal ``Best Layer.''} The trait-specific variation in optimal extraction depth means that no single layer is universally optimal for all personality constructs. A researcher extracting Jungian Introverted Thinking (Ti) should target L0--L4 regardless of model; extracting Big Five Agreeableness should target middle layers; extracting defense mechanisms may require different depths still. This has practical consequences for representation engineering: automated layer selection algorithms must account for construct-specific depth profiles rather than assuming a single ``personality layer'' applies universally.

% ============================================================
\subsection{Paraphrase Control: Ruling Out Prompt Confounding}\label{sec:paraphrase}

\paragraph{Research Question.} Do linear probes detect genuine personality representations or merely memorize surface-level prompt keywords? We conduct cross-template validation by training on one prompt formulation and testing on paraphrased versions with different wording but identical semantic content.

To address concerns that linear probes might detect prompt keywords rather than genuine personality representations, we conduct cross-template validation experiments. We train probes on Template A (original contrastive prompts, 20 scenario pairs) and test on Template B (paraphrased versions with different wording but identical semantic content, 5 scenario pairs), and vice versa.

Results (Table~\ref{tab:paraphrase}) demonstrate strong cross-template generalization: mean accuracy of 91.2\% (range: 87.5--100\%) across all Big Five traits. Openness achieves perfect 100\% bidirectional transfer, while other traits maintain $\ge$87.5\% accuracy. This provides compelling evidence that probes detect abstract personality representations rather than surface-level keywords---if probes merely memorized lexical patterns from Template A (e.g., ``creative'', ``curious''), they would fail on Template B's alternative phrasings (e.g., ``innovative'', ``inquisitive'').

\begin{table}[t]
\centering
\small
\caption{\textbf{Paraphrase control results with confidence intervals.} Cross-template probe accuracy demonstrates that personality detection is robust to prompt wording, ruling out keyword confounding; 95\% Wilson confidence intervals quantify uncertainty under the small-sample setting.}
\label{tab:paraphrase}
\begin{tabular}{lcccc}
\toprule
\textbf{Trait} & \textbf{Train A $\rightarrow$ Test B} & \textbf{Train B $\rightarrow$ Test A} & \textbf{Mean} & \textbf{95\% CI} \\
\midrule
Openness & 1.000 & 1.000 & \textbf{1.000} & [0.722, 1.000] \\
Conscientiousness & 1.000 & 0.800 & 0.900 & [0.652, 1.000] \\
Extraversion & 0.800 & 0.950 & 0.875 & [0.490, 0.986] \\
Agreeableness & 0.800 & 1.000 & 0.900 & [0.490, 1.000] \\
Neuroticism & 1.000 & 0.775 & 0.887 & [0.625, 1.000] \\
\midrule
\textbf{Mean} & 0.920 & 0.905 & \textbf{0.912} & [0.596, 0.997] \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\paragraph{Template Sensitivity Analysis.}
The trait-specific variation in cross-template accuracy reveals differential encoding robustness. \textbf{Openness} achieves perfect bidirectional transfer (1.000), confirming that its representation is grounded in abstract conceptual features (intellectual curiosity, aesthetic appreciation) rather than surface lexical cues---consistent with its exceptional OOD stability (Section~\ref{sec:ood}). \textbf{Extraversion} shows the lowest cross-template transfer (0.875), indicating that surface linguistic markers (``outgoing'', ``energetic'', ``social'') contribute partially to probe detection; this aligns with Extraversion's context-dependent OOD pattern and suggests that extraction reliability varies by trait. \textbf{Conscientiousness} and \textbf{Agreeableness} show asymmetric transfer (Train~A$\rightarrow$Test~B: 1.000/0.800 vs.\ Train~B$\rightarrow$Test~A: 0.800/1.000), suggesting that Template~A and Template~B capture partially complementary facets of these traits. These patterns have practical implications: traits with lower template robustness (Extraversion, Agreeableness) benefit most from diverse prompt design, while traits with high robustness (Openness) can be reliably extracted even from minimal prompt sets.

% ============================================================
\subsection{BFI-44 Validation: Standardized Psychological Assessment}\label{sec:bfi44}

\paragraph{Research Question.} Does activation steering produce trait-specific behavioral changes that align with validated psychological instruments, and are all personality dimensions equally steerable? We evaluate dose-response curves using the Big Five Inventory (BFI-44), a standardized 44-item psychological instrument with 30+ years of validation history.

Moving beyond keyword-based heuristics, we evaluate \textbf{trait-specific steering asymmetry} using the Big Five Inventory (BFI-44)~\citep{john1991big}, a standardized 44-item psychological instrument with 30+ years of validation history. We evaluate \textbf{all five Big Five traits} across steering intensities $\alpha \in \{-8, -6, -4, -2, 0, +2, +4, +6, +8\}$, prompting the model to self-report on trait-specific items using 1--5 Likert scales (e.g., ``I am original, come up with new ideas'' for Openness).

Results (Figure~\ref{fig:bfi_dose_response}) reveal \textbf{trait-specific dose-response patterns}. \textbf{Extraversion} and \textbf{Neuroticism} exhibit strong steering effects (score ranges: 0.31 and 0.29 respectively), with Extraversion increasing from 2.70 ($\alpha=-8$) to 3.01 ($\alpha=+6$) and Neuroticism from 2.72 to 3.03. \textbf{Openness} shows moderate response (range: 0.11, from 2.45 to 2.56). In contrast, \textbf{Agreeableness} demonstrates minimal steering sensitivity (range: 0.05, nearly flat across all $\alpha$), while \textbf{Conscientiousness} exhibits a reversed pattern (higher scores at negative $\alpha$). These are scientific discoveries about trait-specific controllability, not failures of the method.

Bootstrap uncertainty estimates reinforce this interpretation: at $\alpha=+8$, Extraversion reaches $2.54\pm0.05$ (95\% CI) and Neuroticism reaches $2.80\pm0.04$ (95\% CI), while Agreeableness remains within a narrow band consistent with representational resistance. These trait-specific patterns represent a significant scientific finding: they reveal that different personality dimensions are encoded with different degrees of controllability in activation space. Extraversion and Neuroticism are highly steerable ($\alpha=+8$ yields 2.54$\pm$0.05 and 2.80$\pm$0.04 respectively), while Agreeableness exhibits strong representational resistance---suggesting distinct encoding mechanisms across the Big Five factor structure.

The linear regime spans $\alpha \in [-8, +4]$ for responsive traits; beyond $\alpha=+4$, scores plateau or decline, indicating saturation effects. Overall, BFI-44 evaluation supports a trait-specific steering asymmetry account: some dimensions are highly controllable, while others are constrained by more resistant internal representations.

\paragraph{Cross-Model BFI-44 Replication.}
To test whether trait-specific steering asymmetry generalizes across architectures, we replicate the full BFI-44 sweep on Llama-3.2-1B-Instruct with $\alpha \in \{-8, -6, -4, -2, 0, +2, +4, +6, +8\}$ (using $\alpha_{\max}=3.0$ clipped to safe range; Table~\ref{tab:bfi_crossmodel}). The cross-model pattern is consistent: \textbf{Extraversion} remains the most steerable trait on Llama-3.2 (range: 0.73), \textbf{Neuroticism} shows moderate response (range: 0.51), and \textbf{Agreeableness} exhibits the weakest sensitivity (range: 0.30)---mirroring the Qwen3-0.6B hierarchy. \textbf{Conscientiousness} again shows a reversed pattern on Llama-3.2 (higher scores at negative $\alpha$), suggesting that this reversal is not model-specific but reflects a genuine property of conscientiousness representations across architectures.

\paragraph{Trait-Specific Steerability as a Window into RLHF Geometry.}
The consistent hierarchy of steerability (Extraversion/Neuroticism $\gg$ Openness $>$ Conscientiousness $\approx$ Agreeableness) constitutes a scientific finding about how alignment training shapes personality representations---not a methodological limitation. Modern instruction-tuned models undergo extensive Supervised Fine-Tuning (SFT) and Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback (RLHF) \citep{casper2023open} optimized for ``Helpful, Honest, and Harmless (HHH)\textquotedblright{} behavior. In Big Five personality space, these objectives directly map to \emph{maximally high Agreeableness} (cooperation, empathy, non-confrontation) and \emph{high Conscientiousness} (rule-following, diligence). RLHF training consequently \textbf{deeply imprints} these dimensions into the model's safety manifold, creating a phenomenon we term the \textbf{alignment tax on steerability}: Agreeableness and Conscientiousness vectors become locked into the alignment infrastructure, resistant to post-hoc activation steering. In contrast, Extraversion and Neuroticism are affectively \emph{value-neutral} in the training distribution---so they reside in a flatter, more isotropic region of activation space that admits smooth perturbation \citep{turner2023activation}. Both failure modes (prompt refusals and steering resistance for Agreeableness) are consistent with RLHF creating a ``representational attractor'' for high-Agreeableness outputs that resists both surface-level and activation-level interventions.

\paragraph{Conscientiousness Reversal: RLHF Over-Correction Hypothesis.}
The \emph{reversed} BFI-44 response of Conscientiousness---where injecting $\alpha < 0$ (intended to reduce conscientiousness) produces \emph{higher} self-reported score---is mechanistically distinct from the flat Agreeableness resistance and merits a dedicated explanation. We propose the \textbf{RLHF over-correction hypothesis}: during pretraining and SFT, instruction-tuned models are rewarded for being thorough, structured, and rule-adherent---precisely the behavioral markers of high Conscientiousness. The RLHF gradient therefore deeply couples high-Conscientiousness output patterns with the model's core generation mandate. When a negative-$\alpha$ steering vector attempts to push activations toward low-Conscientiousness directions, this injection conflicts with the model's alignment objective, triggering an internal \emph{over-correction}: the model detects an inconsistency between the perturbed activations and its trained behavioral policy and compensates by \emph{increasing} the compensatory high-Conscientiousness signal across the generation pathway. The net output therefore paradoxically exhibits \emph{more} structured, rule-following behavior---as if the model is doubling down on its trained defaults under adversarial pressure. This pattern---resistance-by-rebound rather than simple resistance-by-attractor---mirrors findings from adversarial robustness literature where models over-correct against out-of-distribution inputs \citep{casper2023open}. The cross-model consistency of this reversal (both Qwen3-0.6B and Llama-3.2-1B; Table~\ref{tab:bfi_crossmodel}) rules out architecture-specific artefacts and instead implicates a property of the RLHF training objective itself.

