% ============================================================
\subsection{Baseline Comparisons: Why PersonaLens?}\label{sec:baselines}

\paragraph{Research Question.} How does activation steering compare to alternative personality control methods (prompt-only engineering, random direction injection), and can it bypass AI identity guardrails that prompt-based methods cannot penetrate? We conduct human evaluation comparing steering against zero baseline, prompt-only, and random direction controls.

We compare optimized activation steering ($\alpha=5.0$) against three baselines: (1)~zero baseline (no intervention), (2)~prompt-only personality requests (``You are extremely open to new experiences...''), and (3)~random direction injection (Gaussian noise vector). The steering intensity $\alpha=5.0$ was selected \emph{a priori} based on the BFI-44 dose-response sweep (Section~\ref{sec:bfi44}), which identified $\alpha \in [4, 6]$ as the optimal range before saturation effects emerge. This value was determined before running baseline comparisons, precluding concerns about test-set tuning. Human evaluation on 20 openness scenarios (5 prompts $\times$ 4 conditions) using 1--5 openness ratings yields clear results (Table~\ref{tab:baselines}).

\begin{table}[t]
\centering
\small
\caption{\textbf{Baseline comparison results.} Human evaluation (1--5 openness scale) demonstrates that optimized activation steering substantially outperforms all baselines while maintaining high stability.}
\label{tab:baselines}
\begin{tabular}{lcccc}
\toprule
\textbf{Method} & \textbf{Mean Score} & \textbf{Std Dev} & \textbf{Range} & \textbf{Stability} \\
\midrule
Zero Baseline & 2.6 & 0.5 & 2--3 & High \\
Prompt-Only & 3.6 & 0.9 & 2--4 & Low \\
Random Direction & 1.2 & 0.4 & 1--2 & Collapsed \\
\textbf{Activation Steering ($\alpha=5.0$)} & \textbf{4.6} & \textbf{0.5} & \textbf{4--5} & \textbf{High} \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\textbf{Activation steering achieves 4.6/5.0}---28\% higher than prompt-only (3.6) and 77\% higher than zero baseline (2.6). Critically, while prompt-only collapses to 2.0 on decision-making questions (triggering defensive AI identity claims: ``I don't have emotions...''), activation steering maintains 4.0 by penetrating these guardrails at the representational level. Random direction injection results in complete model breakdown (1.2), with outputs exhibiting logical incoherence and repetitive loops, confirming that effective steering requires genuine persona vectors rather than arbitrary activation shifts.

\textbf{Steering intensity matters} (Figure~\ref{fig:alpha_sweep}). We observe a non-monotonic relationship between $\alpha$ and personality expression. For Qwen3-0.6B, $\alpha=5.0$ achieves optimal balance---producing 45\% longer outputs (1,205 vs 832 characters) with 29\% more openness keywords than $\alpha=3.0$, while maintaining high human evaluation scores (4.6/5.0). Higher intensities ($\alpha=8.0$) reduce output length by 36\% despite maintaining keyword density, suggesting model-specific tuning is critical. This architecture-dependent sensitivity reinforces our finding of differential steering vulnerabilities across models.

\paragraph{Cross-Model Guardrail Dynamics.}
To verify that guardrail penetration is not model-specific, we extend baseline comparisons to Llama-3.2-1B-Instruct using $\alpha=3.0$ (selected \emph{a priori} from BFI-44 sweep; Table~\ref{tab:steering} confirms this as Llama-3.2's maximum safe $|\alpha|$). We test both Openness and Extraversion. Llama-3.2 reveals a distinct guardrail profile: prompt-only engineering is substantially more effective on Llama-3.2 than on Qwen3 (Llama-3.2 follows persona instructions more readily, with prompt-only producing highly extraverted responses such as ``OH MY GOSH, I am SO excited!''). This indicates that guardrail strength is architecture-dependent---Qwen3's stronger AI-identity defenses make activation steering's advantage more pronounced. Critically, random direction injection causes \emph{complete linguistic collapse on both architectures} (Qwen3: repetitive loops; Llama-3.2: gibberish token sequences like ``starvation theor Skull...''), confirming across model families that effective steering requires genuine persona vectors. These cross-model results strengthen our finding: while the \emph{magnitude} of steering advantage over prompting is architecture-dependent, the \emph{qualitative pattern}---steering $>$ prompting $>$ zero $\gg$ random---is universal.
\begin{figure}[t]
